# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ce-marking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] The Directive provides common broad objectives for safety regulations, so that electrical equipment approved by any EU member country will be acceptable for use in all other EU countries.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] The Low Voltage Directive does not supply any specific technical standards that must be met, instead relying on IEC technical standards to guide designers to produce safe products.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] Products that conform to the general principles of the Low Voltage Directive and the relevant particular safety standards are marked with the CE marking to indicate compliance and acceptance throughout the EU.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] Conformance is asserted by the manufacturer, based on its conformity assessment.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] This directive updated and replaced **2006/95/EC**.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] The directive covers electrical equipment designed for use with a voltage rating of between 50 and 1000 volts for alternating current (AC) or between 75 and 1500 volts for direct current (DC).
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] Importantly, it does not cover voltages within equipment.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] The directive does not cover components (broadly, this refers to individual electronic components).
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] Certain classes of equipment, covered by other technical standards, are listed in Annex II of the Directive as excluded from its scope.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] These items include medical devices, electricity meters, railway or maritime equipment, and electrical plugs and sockets for domestic use.
[src:ce-marking/35-eu] In the United Kingdom, the directive is implemented by "The Electrical Equipment (Safety) Regulations 2016".
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:ce-marking/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] Accreditation bodies are established in many economies with the primary purpose of ensuring that conformity assessment bodies are subject to oversight by an authoritative body.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] Accreditation bodies that have been peer-evaluated as competent sign regional and international arrangements to demonstrate their competence.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] These accreditation bodies then assess and accredit conformity assessment bodies to the relevant standards.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] An authoritative body that performs accreditation is called an 'accreditation body'.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] The International Accreditation Forum (IAF) and International Laboratory Accreditation Cooperation (ILAC) provide international recognitions to accreditation bodies.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] There are many internationally recognized accreditation bodies approved by the IAF and ILAC.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] In East Asia, the China National Accreditation Board is the largest, while the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) is the largest in Europe.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] The National Association of Testing Authorities (NATA) and the Joint Accreditation System of Australia and New Zealand (JAS-ANZ) being the largest in the Oceania region, with the South African National Accreditation System being the largest in Africa.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] For most of the accreditation schemes, international standards issued by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) are used.
[src:ce-marking/accreditation] Many accreditation bodies, such as the UKAS, EIAC, EGAC, PNAC, IAS, NABCB operate according to processes developed by the ISO as specified in ISO/IEC 17011.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] There is a high chance that the concepts of aerosol go as far back as 1790.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The first aerosol spray can patent was granted in Oslo in 1927 to Erik Rotheim, a Norwegian chemical engineer, and a United States patent was granted for the invention in 1931.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The patent rights were sold to a United States company for 100,000 Norwegian kroner.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The Norwegian Postal Service, Posten Norge, celebrated the invention by issuing a stamp in 1998.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Kahn received a patent for a disposable spray can, but the product remained largely undeveloped.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Kahn's idea was to mix cream and a propellant from two sources to make whipped cream at home—not a true aerosol in that sense.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Moreover, in 1949, he disclaimed his first four claims, which were the foundation of his following patent claims.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] It was not until 1941 that the aerosol spray can was first put to effective use by Americans Lyle Goodhue and William Sullivan of the United States Bureau of Entomology and Plant Quarantine, who are credited as the inventors of the modern spray can.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Their design of a refillable spray can, dubbed the **aerosol bomb** or **bug bomb**, is the ancestor of many commercial spray products.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] It was a hand-sized steel can charged with a liquefied gas under 75 pounds of pressure and a product to be expelled as a mist or a foam.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] A public-service patent was issued on the invention and assigned to the Secretary of Agriculture for the free use of the people of the United States.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Pressurized by liquefied gas, which gave it propellant qualities, the small, portable can enabled soldiers to defend themselves against malaria-carrying mosquitoes by spraying inside tents and airplanes in the Pacific during World War II.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Goodhue and Sullivan received the first Erik Rotheim Gold Medal from the Federation of European Aerosol Associations on August 28, 1970, in Oslo, Norway in recognition of their early patents and subsequent pioneering work with aerosol sprays.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] In 1948, three companies were granted licenses by the United States government to manufacture aerosol sprays.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Two of the three companies, Chase Products Company and Claire Manufacturing, continue to manufacture aerosol sprays.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The "crimp-on valve", used to control the spray in low-pressure aerosol sprays was developed in 1949 by Bronx machine shop proprietor Robert H.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Molina proposed that chlorofluorocarbons, used as propellants in aerosol sprays, contributed to the depletion of Earth's ozone layer.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Congress passed amendments to the Clean Air Act in 1977 authorizing the Environmental Protection Agency to regulate the presence of CFCs in the atmosphere.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The United Nations Environment Programme called for ozone layer research that same year, and, in 1981, authorized a global framework convention on ozone layer protection.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Gardiner, and Jon Shanklin published the first scientific paper detailing the hole in the ozone layer.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] That same year, the Vienna Convention was signed in response to the UN's authorization.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Two years later, the Montreal Protocol, which regulated the production of CFCs was formally signed.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The U.S. formally phased out CFCs in 1995.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] If aerosol cans were simply filled with compressed gas, it would either need to be at a dangerously high pressure and require special pressure vessel design (like in gas cylinders), or the amount of payload in the can would be small, and rapidly deplete.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Usually, the gas is the vapor of a liquid with boiling point slightly lower than room temperature.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] This means that inside the pressurized can, the vapor can exist in equilibrium with its bulk liquid at a pressure that is higher than atmospheric pressure (and able to expel the payload), but not dangerously high.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] As gas escapes, it is immediately replaced by evaporating liquid.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Since the propellant exists in liquid form in the can, it should be miscible with the payload or dissolved in the payload.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] In gas dusters and freeze sprays, the payload itself acts as the propellant.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The propellant in a gas duster can is not "compressed air" as sometimes assumed, but usually a haloalkane.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) were once often used as propellants, but since the Montreal Protocol came into force in 1989, they have been replaced in nearly every country due to the negative effects CFCs have on Earth's ozone layer.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The most common replacements of CFCs are mixtures of volatile hydrocarbons, typically propane, n-butane and isobutane.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Dimethyl ether (DME) and methyl ethyl ether are also used.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] All these have the disadvantage of being flammable.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Nitrous oxide and carbon dioxide are also used as propellants to deliver foodstuffs (for example, whipped cream and cooking spray).
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Medicinal aerosols such as asthma inhalers use hydrofluoroalkanes (HFA): either HFA 134a (1,1,1,2,-tetrafluoroethane) or HFA 227 (1,1,1,2,3,3,3-heptafluoropropane) or combinations of the two.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] More recently, liquid hydrofluoroolefin (HFO) propellants have become more widely adopted in aerosol systems due to their relatively low vapor pressure, low global warming potential (GWP), and nonflammability.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Liquid aerosol propellant filling machines require additional precautions, such as being mounted externally to the production warehouse in a gas house.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Liquid aerosol propellant machines are typically constructed to comply with ATEX Zone II/2G regulations (classification Zone 1).
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Modern aerosol spray products have three major parts: the can, the valve and the actuator or button.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The can is most commonly lacquered tinplate (steel with a layer of tin) and may be made of two or three pieces of metal crimped together.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Aluminium cans are also common and are generally used for products that are more expensive or intended to have a more premium appearance, such as personal care products.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The valve is crimped to the inside rim of the can, and the design of this component is important in determining the spray rate.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The actuator is depressed by the user to open the valve; a spring closes the valve again when it is released.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The shape and size of the nozzle in the actuator controls the aerosolized particle size and the spread of the aerosol spray.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] True aerosol sprays release their propellant during use.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Some non-propellant alternatives include various spray bottles, squeeze bottles, and Bag on Valve (BoV) or Bag in Can (BiC) compressed gas aerosol systems.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Packaging that uses a piston barrier system by CCL Industries or EarthSafe by Crown Holdings is often selected for highly viscous products such as post-foaming hair gels, thick creams and lotions, food spreads and industrial products and sealants.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The main benefit of this system is that it eliminates gas permeation and assures separation of the product from the propellant, maintaining the purity and integrity of the formulation throughout its consumer lifespan.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The piston barrier system also provides a consistent flow rate with minimal product retention.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Another type of dispensing system is the bag-in-can (or BOV, bag-on-valve technology) system where the product is separated from the pressurizing agent with a hermetically sealed, multi-layered laminated pouch, which maintains complete formulation integrity so only pure product is dispensed.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Among its many benefits, the bag-in-can system extends a product's shelf life, is suitable for all-attitude, (360-degree) dispensing, quiet and non-chilling discharge.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] One key performance difference relative to true aerosol systems is that traditional BoV dispensing pressures, BoVs pressurized solely by pressurized gas) drops as the product is dispensed.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] This bag-in-can system is used in the packaging of pharmaceutical, industrial, household, pet care and other products that require complete separation between the product and the propellant or require near complete evacuation of thin to viscous formulations.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] A later development is the 2K (two component) aerosol spray, with a main component stored in a main chamber, and a second component stored in an accessory container.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] When an applicator activates the 2K aerosol by breaking the accessory container, the two components mix.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The 2K aerosol can is advantageous for delivery of reactive mixtures; for example, a 2K reactive mixture can use low molecular weight monomer, oligomer, and functionalized low molecular polymer to make a final cross-linked high molecular weight polymer.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] A 2K aerosol can increase solid contents and deliver high-performance polymer products, such as curable paints, foams, and adhesives.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] In the United States, non-empty aerosol cans are considered hazardous waste, but are still considered "recyclable when empty" in US curbside recycling programs.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Aerosol products in the European Union must comply with health and safety regulations as set out in Directive 75/324/EEC. which established the "**reversed epsilon**" mark.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] This marking is required for aerosol products over 50ml.
[src:ce-marking/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The same marking is also used in the United Kingdom, although the UKCA marking is planned to replace it in Great Britain.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] The term agmark was coined by joining the words 'Ag' to mean agriculture and 'mark' for a certification mark.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] This term was introduced originally in the bill presented in the parliament of India for the *Agricultural Produce (Grading and Marking) Act*.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] The entire system of Agmark, including the name, was created by Archibald MacDonald Livingstone, Agricultural and Marketing Advisory to the Government of India, from 1934 to 1941.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] He was supported by a staff of several hundred.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] The system was designed to benefit local growers throughout India who were, in the absence of a certification as to quality, exposed to receiving less for their produce from dealers than its true worth.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] The Agmark certification is employed through fully state-owned Agmark laboratories located across the nation which act as testing and certifying centres.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] In addition to the *Central AGMARK Laboratory (CAL)* in Nagpur, there are *Regional AGMARK Laboratories (RALs)* in 11 nodal cities (Mumbai, New Delhi, Chennai, Kolkata, Kanpur, Kochi, Guntur, Amritsar, Jaipur, Rajkot, Bhopal).
[src:ce-marking/agmark] Each of the regional laboratories is equipped with and specializes in the testing of products of regional significance.
[src:ce-marking/agmark] Hence the product range that could be tested varies across the centres.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC provides technical expertise and advice drawn from a network of consumer representatives across Europe.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] On 15 June 2022, an Extraordinary General Meeting of the association adopted new Statutes.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The most visible modifications introduced by the Statutes were the change in the legal title of the association, and the change in the title of the lead executive from Secretary-General to Director-General.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC was set up in 1995 as an international non-profit association under Belgian law.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] Its principal motivation was to ensure organised consumer participation in the development of European Standards intended to support European legislation introduced under the New Approach to Technical Harmonization and Standardization.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] However, its competence also extends to other European Standards developed by the European Standardization Organisations, as well as to other standards that may impact directly or indirectly on the European consumer (for example, certain standards of W3C, the World Wide Web Consortium).
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC is open to the representation of consumer organisations from the 27 European Union Member States and the United Kingdom, three European Free Trade Association (EFTA) countries (Iceland, Norway and Switzerland) as well as North Macedonia, Serbia and Turkey.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The organisation's General Assembly is composed of one national member per country, nominated jointly by the national consumer organisations in that country.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] These areas of priority respond to the needs voiced through the General Assembly by the national consumer organisations.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC reimburses the travel, accommodation and subsistence costs of its volunteers, and pays a daily allowance.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] Regarding services, ANEC is primarily concerned with the safety of services, rather than their quality which is of secondary concern.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] It does not strive to eliminate all diversity in services, but rather demands that certain core safety requirements need to be complied with by providers to ensure all customers' wellbeing through standardisation.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] Nevertheless, it believes a horizontal legislative framework for the safety of services is needed, in other words, an extension of the "New Approach" to services.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] Van Leeuwen (2017) claims that ANEC lacks the human resources and technical expertise to play a major role in the process of European standardisation, and is able to obtain achievements on only a limited number of consumer protection issues.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC confirms that the 'national delegation principle' means it "does not have a central role in the European Standardisation System".
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC is funded by the European Union (95%) and EFTA (5%) for its core mission under Regulation (EU) 1025/2012, while the time of the representatives of the national consumer organisations and experts is accepted by the EU and EFTA as a "contribution in kind".
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] In 2020, the grant made available to ANEC was 1.44 million euros.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The ANEC secretariat calculated the "contribution in kind" in 2007 to be worth 260.000 euros.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The contribution was calculated to be worth 516.000 euros in 2020, and 620.000 euros in 2022.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The ANEC secretariat is based in Brussels.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] In October 2020, the secretariat relocated to rue d'Arlon 80, the same premises as The European Consumer Organisation (BEUC).
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The secretariat team is responsible for leading the political activities of the association.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] ANEC has signed the European Union's Transparency Register (with identification number 507800799-30) and accepted its code of conduct.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] On 15 June 2023, Dermott Jewell (Ireland) was re-elected ANEC president for the term 2023 to 2027.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] Rusnė Juozapaitienė (Lithuania) was elected vice-president, and Olav Kasland (Norway) was elected treasurer.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] In December 2025, Jens Henriksson (Sweden) succeeded Rusnė Juozapaitienė as vice-president.
[src:ce-marking/anec-organisation] The director-general is Stephen Russell.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The **ATEX directives** are two of the EU directives describing the minimum safety requirements for workplaces and equipment used in explosive atmospheres.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The name is an initialization of the term *ATmosphères EXplosives* (French for "explosive atmospheres").
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Organizations in the EU must follow Directives to protect employees from explosion risk in areas with an explosive atmosphere.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Note: The ATEX 95 "equipment" Directive 94/9/EC, was withdrawn on 20 April 2016 when it was replaced by ATEX 114 Directive 2014/34/EU.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] ATEX Directive 2014/34/EU is mandatory for manufacturers as of 20 April 2016 as stated in article 44 of the Directive.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] ATEX Directive 2014/34/EU was published on 29 March 2014, by the European Parliament.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] It refers to the harmonization of the laws of the Member States relating to equipment and protective systems intended for use in potentially explosive atmospheres.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Regarding ATEX 99/92/EC Directive, the requirement is that Employers must classify areas where potentially explosive atmospheres may occur, into zones.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The classification given to a particular zone, and its size and location, depends on the likelihood of an explosive atmosphere occurring and its persistence if it does.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Equipment in use before July 2003 is allowed to be used indefinitely provided a risk assessment shows it is safe to do so.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The aim of Directive 2014/34/EU is to allow the free trade of ‘ATEX’ equipment and protective systems within the EU by removing the need for separate testing and documentation for each member state.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The regulations apply to all equipment intended for use in explosive atmospheres, whether electrical or mechanical, including protective systems.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] There are two categories of equipment: 'I' for mining and 'II' for surface industries.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Manufacturers who apply its provisions and affix the CE marking and the Ex marking are able to sell their equipment anywhere within the European Union without any further requirements with respect to the risks covered being applied.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The directive covers a large range of equipment, potentially including equipment used on fixed offshore platforms, in petrochemical plants, mines, flour mills, and other areas where a potentially explosive atmosphere may be present.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] In very broad terms, there are three preconditions for the directive to apply: the equipment must (a) have its own effective source of ignition, (b) be intended for use in a potentially explosive atmosphere (air mixtures), and (c) be under normal atmospheric conditions.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The directive also covers components essential for the safe use and safety devices directly contributing to the safe use of the equipment in scope.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] These latter devices may be outside the potentially explosive environment.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Manufacturers/suppliers (or importers, if the manufacturers are outside the EU) must ensure that their products meet essential health and safety requirements and undergo appropriate conformity procedures.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] This usually involves testing and certification by a ‘third-party’ certification body (known as a Notified Body e.g.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] UL, Vinçotte, Intertek, Sira, Baseefa, Lloyd's, TUV ICQC) but manufacturers/suppliers can ‘self-certify’ Category 3 equipment (technical dossier including drawings, hazard analysis and users manual in the local language) and Category 2 non-electrical equipment.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Still, for Category 2 the technical dossier must be lodged with a notified body.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Once certified, the equipment is marked by the ‘CE’ (meaning it complies with ATEX and all other relevant directives) and the ‘Ex’ symbol to identify it as approved under the ATEX directive.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The technical dossier must be kept for a period of 10 years.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Certification ensures that the equipment or protective system is fit for its intended purpose and that adequate information is supplied with it to ensure that it can be used safely.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] In DSEAR, an explosive atmosphere is defined as a mixture of dangerous substances under certain atmospheric conditions that are part of the air.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] They are in the form of gases or airborne particulates, in which, after ignition has occurred, combustion will spread to the entire mixture.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The aforementioned atmospheric conditions are temperatures of −20 to 40°C, and pressures of 0.8 to 1.1 bar.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The ATEX Directive covers explosions from flammable gas/vapors and combustible dust/fibers (which, contrary to common belief, can lead to hazardous explosions).
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The following are classifications for zones that can produce explosive atmospheres.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The following zones are each defined as a place in which an explosive atmosphere consisting of a mixture of air or dangerous substances in the form of gas, vapor, or mist...
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] These are defined as a place in which an explosive atmosphere is in the form of a cloud of combustible dust in the air...
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] "Effective ignition source" is a term defined in the European ATEX directive as an event that, in combination with sufficient oxygen and fuel, can cause an explosion.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Methane, hydrogen, and coal dust are good examples of possible fuels.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The **Dangerous Substances and Explosive Atmospheres Regulations 2002** (SI 2002/2776), or **DSEAR**, is the United Kingdom's implementation of the ATEX directive.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The intention of the Regulations is to reduce the risk of a fatality or serious injury resulting from a "dangerous substance" igniting and potentially exploding.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] Examples of a "dangerous substance", as defined by DSEAR, include sawdust, ethanol vapours, and hydrogen gas.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] The regulation is enforceable by the HSE or local authorities.
[src:ce-marking/atex-directive] From June 2015, DSEAR incorporated changes in the EU Chemical Agents Directive and now also covers gases under pressure and substances that are corrosive to metals.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The mark indicates that the product may be traded freely in any part of the European Economic Area, regardless of its country of origin.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] It consists of the CE letter pair and, if applicable, the four digit identification number of the notified body involved in the conformity assessment procedure.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The CE mark on a product indicates that the manufacturer or importer of that product affirms its compliance with the relevant EU legislation and the product may be sold anywhere in the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] It is a criminal offence to affix a CE mark to a product that is not compliant or to offer such a product for sale.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] For example, most electrical products must comply with the Low Voltage Directive and the EMC Directive, among others; toys must comply with the Toy Safety Directive.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In the case of electrical products, several later norms such as the Restriction of Hazardous Substances Directive (RoHS) and Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive (WEEE) are relevant in addition to the Low Voltage Directive and EMC Directive.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The exact significance of the CE mark therefore depends on when it was applied to a specific unit.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The marking does not indicate EEA manufacture or that the EU or another authority has approved a product as safe or conformant.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The EU requirements may include safety, health, and environmental protection.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] If stipulated in any EU product legislation, assessment by a Notified Body or manufacture according to a certified production quality system may be required.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Where relevant, the CE mark is followed by the registration number of the notified body involved in conformity assessment.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Not all products need CE marking to be traded in the EEA; only product categories subject to relevant directives or regulations are required (and allowed) to bear CE marking.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Although it has been suggested that the CE letter pair is an abbreviation of ***conformité européenne*** (as used, for example, in a written question in the European Parliament), this meaning appears to be a backronym.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] None of the defining EU Directives or EU Regulations give this association.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] When the Commission replied to the written question, they did not repeat or acknowledge those words.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] However, in a 2014 press release, the Commission gave CE as an abbreviation of *conformité européenne*.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] This is the only quasi-validation of the term that has been publicly released by a European authority.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] CE marking is mandatory for certain product groups intended for sale within the European Union, the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), and Turkey.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] As Northern Ireland (a region of the UK) remains aligned to the European Single Market under the Northern Ireland Protocol, CE marking remains mandatory for products placed on the market there, and the British UKCA mark is not required.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The formal legal status of the CE mark is set out in various EU Directives and Regulations.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The underlying principles are explained in the Commission's "Blue Guide".
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Responsibility for CE marking lies with whoever puts the product on the market in the EU, i.e. an EU-based manufacturer, the importer or distributor of a product made outside the EU, or an EU-based office of a non-EU manufacturer.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The manufacturer of a product affixes the CE marking to it but has to take certain obligatory steps before the product can bear CE marking.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The manufacturer must carry out a conformity assessment, set up a technical file, and sign a Declaration stipulated by the leading legislation for the product.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The documentation has to be made available to authorities on request.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Importers of products have to verify that the manufacturer outside the EU has undertaken the necessary steps and that the documentation is available upon request.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Importers should also make sure that contact with the manufacturer can always be established.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Distributors must be able to demonstrate to national authorities that they have acted with due care and they must have affirmation from the manufacturer or importer that the necessary measures have been taken.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] If importers or distributors market the products under their own name, they take over the manufacturer's responsibilities.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In this case they must have sufficient information on the design and production of the product, as they will be assuming the legal responsibility when they affix the CE marking.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] A guide to the implementation of directives and regulations based on the New Approach and the Global Approach (the "Blue Guide") was first published by the European Union in 2000.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Updated versions were published on 28 February 2014 and 26 July 2016.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Depending on the level of risk of the product, the CE marking is affixed to a product by the manufacturer or authorized representative who needs to ensure that the product meets all the CE marking requirements.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In some cases, if a product has minimal risk, it can be self-certified by a manufacturer making a declaration of conformity and affixing the CE marking to their own product.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Self-certification exists only for products that have a minimal risk for their use, and this is clearly foreseen in the relevant directive and regulation according to the product "category".
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Choose the conformity assessment procedure from the modules called out by the directive or the regulation for the product according to each category (level of risk) involved.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] There are several modules available for the Conformity Assessment Procedures, but only a few of them involve self-certification.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The most of these procedure require a "type Approval" and a Production conformity assessment by a Notified Body.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] All procedures (modules) of certification are as listed below which are derivered from Article 5.1.7 of "Blue Guide".
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The level of risk is defined by the "category" of each equipment.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The higher the category, the higher the risk.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] After defining the category, the manufacturer, in order to obtain certification, shall then apply the relevant procedures for the specific category of the product or choose the relevant procedures for a higher-category product.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The manufacturer, after insuring that the relevant modules for the product category have been applied, will affix the CE mark and draw up a Declaration of Conformity.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The Declaration of Conformity contains a description of the product, the directive(s) and regulation(s) applied, the product category for each directive or regulation, the module chosen, and the name and registration number of the notified body involved in certification procedures (models).
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Notified bodies involved in certification procedures are organizations that have been nominated by a member state (according to an accreditation procedure) and have been notified by the European Commission.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] These notified bodies act as Independent Inspection organizations and carry out the procedures as listed in the relevant Modules applied as stated by the relevant directives and regulations.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] A manufacturer can choose any notified body (notified for the certain directive or regulation and relevant Modules) in any Member State of the European Union.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The first step is to identify whether the product needs to bear CE marking or not.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Not all products are required to bear CE marking, only the products that fall within the scope of at least one of the sectoral norms (directives and regulations) requiring CE marking.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] There are more than 20 sectoral product norms requiring CE marking covering, but not limited to, products such as electrical equipment, machines, medical devices, toys, pressure equipment, PPE, wireless devices and construction products.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Identifying which norm(s) may be applicable, as there may be more than one, involves a simple exercise of reading the scope of each norm to establish which apply to the product (Such as the "Low Voltage Directive," 2014/35/EU).
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] If the product does not fall within the scope of any of the sectoral norm, then the product does not need to bear CE marking (and, indeed, must not bear CE marking).
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Each norm has slightly different methods of demonstrating conformity depending on the classification of the product and its intended use.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Every Directive or Regulation has a number of 'essential requirements' that the product has to meet before being placed on the market.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The best way to demonstrate that these essential requirements have been met is by meeting the requirements of an applicable 'harmonised standard,’ which offer a presumption of conformity to the essential requirements, although the use of standards usually remains voluntary.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Harmonised standards can be identified by searching the 'Official Journal' on the European Commission's website, or by visiting the New Approach website established by the European Commission and EFTA with the European Standardisation Organisations.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The process is not always a self-declaration process, there are various 'attestation routes' to conformity depending on the Directive or Regulation and classification of the product.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Many products (such as invasive medical devices, or fire alarm and extinguisher systems, Pressure Equipment, Lifts etc.) in most cases, have a mandatory requirement for the involvement of an authorised third party e.g. a "notified body".
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] When all of the requirements have been established, the conformity of the product to the essential requirements of the norm(s) needs to be assessed.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] This usually involves assessment and/or testing, and may include an evaluation of the conformity of the product to the harmonised standard(s) identified in step 2.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Technical documentation, usually referred to as the technical file, relating to the product or range of products needs to be compiled.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] This information should cover every aspect relating to conformity and is likely to include details of the design, development and manufacture of the product.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] When the manufacturer, importer or authorised representative is satisfied that their product conforms to the applicable norms, an EU declaration of conformity must be completed or, for partly completed machinery under the Machinery Directive, an ECU declaration of incorporation.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Under the General Product Safety Regulation (EU) 2023/988 (GPSR), the EU declaration of conformity is a mandatory legal document in which the manufacturer or authorised representative declares that a product complies with all applicable safety requirements.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The declaration is part of the product’s technical documentation and must be submitted to competent authorities on request.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] There are numerous 'Agreements on Mutual Recognition of Conformity Assessment' between the European Union and other countries such as the US, Japan, Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Israel.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Consequently, CE marking is now found on many products from these countries.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Japan has its own marking known as the Conformity Mark.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Switzerland and Turkey (which are not members of the EEA) also require products to bear CE marking as an affirmation of conformity.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] When the manufacturer of a machine puts the CE marking, it engages itself and guarantees, that it makes all the tests, assessments and evaluation on the product to conform to all the requirements of *all* the norms that apply to its product.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The European Commission is aware that CE markings, like other certifications marks, are misused.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] CE marking is sometimes affixed to products that do not fulfill the legal requirements and conditions, or it is affixed to products for which it is not required.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In one case it was reported that "Chinese manufacturers were submitting well-engineered electrical products to obtain conformity testing reports, but then removing non-essential components in production to reduce costs".
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] There are also cases in which the product complies with the applicable requirements, but the form, dimensions, or proportions of the mark itself are not as specified in the legislation.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In 2008, a logo very similar to CE marking was alleged to exist and to stand for *China Export* because some Chinese manufacturers apply it to their products.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] However, the European Commission says that this is a misconception.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The matter was raised at the European Parliament in 2008.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The Commission responded that it was unaware of the existence of any "Chinese Export" mark and that, in its view, the misunderstanding had arisen because a producer had failed to respect the precise dimensions and proportions of the mark as prescribed in the legislation.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The Commission was also aware of fraudulent misuse of the mark on products that did not comply with the standards, but that this is a separate issue.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] It had initiated the procedure to register CE marking as a Community collective trademark, and was in discussion with Chinese authorities to ensure compliance with EU legislation.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Chinese (and other non-EU) manufacturers are permitted to use the CE mark provided that the goods have been manufactured in accordance with the relevant EU directives and regulations.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Nevertheless, and despite the Commission's assurance that it is without foundation, this urban myth continues to propagate on many websites.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In March 2017, another question was put to the European Commission on the statistics of the fraudulent use of the CE mark, reasserting the "China Export" myth.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In reply, the Commission notes that it is the responsibility of Member States to take legal action on infringements; the Commission does not have statistics on the penalties that were imposed by Member States for the improper use of the CE marking.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In an IEEE conference paper studying the origins and evolution of the claim, the author concludes there is no evidence of a fraudulent "China Export" sign.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In addition, similar "fraudulent" marking can be found in many European and American made products which do not show apparent noncompliance.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Typesetting C and E too near to each other is probably just a typesetting mistake.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The possibly earliest mention of "China Export" can be found on a Finnish fishing-themed discussion forum on year 2004.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The author suspects the origins start from a joke: someone has invented a funny meaning for the abbreviation CE, from which the claim has evolved as oral history and turned into a widespread myth.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Repeating the myth as a European parliamentary question has reinforced the credibility of the myth.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Directive 2014/35/EU, the "Low Voltage Directive", specifically excludes (amongst other things) *plugs and socket outlets for domestic use* which are not covered by any Union norm and therefore should not be CE marked.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Throughout the EU, as in other jurisdictions, the control of *plugs and socket outlets for domestic use* is subject to national regulations.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] It is fairly common to see domestic sockets (and adaptors) that have an inbuilt 5 volt USB-A power supply socket in addition to conventional 'two-pin + earth' AC sockets.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] These sockets must be CE marked, but the CE mark applies to the 5 volt converter *only* and not the rest of the socket or adaptor.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] This is comparable to dedicated 5 volt power supplies.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] There are mechanisms in place to ensure that the CE marking is put on products correctly.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Controlling products bearing CE marking is the responsibility of public authorities in member states, in cooperation with the European Commission.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Citizens may contact national market surveillance authorities if the misuse of the CE marking is suspected or if a product's safety is questioned.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] In the UK, sale of any product that carries a CE mark that is not so approved, or outside the scope of approval is a specific offence under Section 1 of the Trade Descriptions Act 1968.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The seller of such an article is as equally guilty as the manufacturer or importer.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Ignorance as to the true status of the sold item is no defence against a prosecution (strict liability).
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Under the Act, the misrepresentation is that the sold item conforms to a specification that it does not or that there is no such specification to which it can conform.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The procedures, measures and sanctions applying to counterfeiting of the CE marking vary according to the respective member state's national administrative and penal legislation.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] Depending on the seriousness of the crime, economic operators may be liable to a fine and, in some circumstances, imprisonment.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] However, if the product is not regarded as an imminent safety risk, the manufacturer may be given an opportunity to ensure that the product is in conformity with the applicable legislation before being forced to take the product off the market.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The mark does not have a Unicode code point.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] According to the Unicode principles, rendering the mark is a computer font design choice for the two ordinary upper-case letters, C and E, with a specific kerning arrangement.
[src:ce-marking/ce-marking] The exact geometry that constitutes the mark is provided in the vector graphics files available from the European Commission.
